## ❓ PART 9 — Questions You Might Be Asked & How to Answer

**Q: Why use Socket.IO instead of just REST API?**
> REST API is request-response — you have to ask for data. Socket.IO is persistent — the server can PUSH data to everyone at any time. For a live quiz where 30 students need to see the same leaderboard update simultaneously, REST would require constant polling. Socket.IO is the right tool.

**Q: Why is registration disabled?**
> The app is designed for a closed classroom environment. The admin pre-creates all student accounts (bulk imported from student data). This prevents unauthorized access.

**Q: What happens if the server restarts during a live quiz?**
> `roomState` (in-memory Map) is lost. However, on reconnect, the server has a `reconnectUser` handler that **rebuilds state from the database** (fetching all Results and rebuilding the leaderboard and progress). The quiz can continue.

**Q: How does the AI quiz generation work?**
> A carefully crafted text prompt is sent directly to Google's Gemini API over HTTPS. The prompt instructs Gemini to return ONLY valid JSON in a specific format. The server parses the response and validates the questions before saving them.

**Q: How is the leaderboard tie-breaking done?**
> 3 levels: 1) Highest score wins. 2) If same score, lower total time wins (faster is better). 3) If same score AND same time, whoever submitted their last answer first wins (using `lastAnsweredAt` timestamp).
